{{about|containers used for recycling|the place in a file system where deleted items are stored|Trash (computing)|the Sigur Rós album commonly known as Recycle Bin|Von brigði}} {{one source|date=May 2018}} [[Image:Hazleton.jpg|right|thumb|Custom bin design featuring advertising in [[Toronto]], Canada and United States]] [[Image:RecyclingStationOxford20040828.jpg|right|thumb|Recycle station in [[Oxford]], England]] [[Image:Recycling-bin.JPG|right|thumb|A household recycling bin issued by a local council]] [[File:2008-07-12 Durham recycling bins at the curb.jpg|thumb|[[Durham, North Carolina|Durham]] recycling containers ready for pickup on the curb of Vickers Avenue]] [[File:Zaanstad-Glass-recycling-bin-0305.jpg|thumb|Recycling bin for glass near [[Zaanstad]]]] A '''recycling bin''' (or '''recycle bin''') is a container used to hold recyclables before they are taken to [[Materials recovery facility|recycling center]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=ECYCLER|url=http://ecycler.com/recycle-bin|work=sustainability|accessdate=23 April 2011|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110815113155/http://ecycler.com/recycle-bin|archivedate=15 August 2011|df=}}</ref> Recycling bins exist in various sizes for use inside and outside [[home]]s, [[office]]s, and large public facilities. Separate containers are often provided for [[paper]], [[tin]] or [[aluminum]] [[Tin can|cans]], and [[glass]] or [[plastic bottle]]s, or may be commingled.
Many recycling bins are designed to be easily recognizable, and are marked with slogans promoting recycling on a blue or green background along with the universal [[recycling]] symbol. Others are intentionally unobtrusive. Bins are sometimes in different colors so that user may differentiate between the types of materials to be placed in them. While there is no universal standard, the color blue is commonly used to indicate a bin is for recycling in public settings.
Recycling bins or cans, or carts are a common element of municipal [[kerbside collection]] programs, which frequently distribute the bins to encourage participation.
